# Meet The Tiny EtherCAT Machine

```elixir
Mix.install([
  {:ethercat, github: "sid2baker/ethercat", override: true},
  {:kino_ethercat, github: "sid2baker/kino_ethercat"}
])
```

## Scene 1: The Whole World

One master. Three slaves. That is enough for the first story.

```mermaid
flowchart LR
  M[Master] --> C

  subgraph S[Slaves]
    C[Coupler]
    I[Inputs]
    O[Outputs]
    C --> I
    I --> O
  end
```

## Scene 2: What The Master Does

The master uses cyclic EtherCAT frames.

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
  participant M as Master
  participant R as EtherCAT ring
  M->>R: cyclic EtherCAT frame
  R-->>M: inputs + working counter
  M->>M: check the cycle
```

## Scene 3: Bring It To Life

Evaluate the simulator cell, then follow the instructions shown by the simulator workspace.

<!-- livebook:{"attrs":"","chunks":null,"kind":"Elixir.KinoEtherCAT.SmartCells.Simulator","livebook_object":"smart_cell"} -->

```elixir
alias EtherCAT.Simulator
alias EtherCAT.Simulator.Slave

simulator_ip = {127, 0, 0, 2}

_ = Simulator.stop()

devices = [
  Slave.from_driver(KinoEtherCAT.Driver.EK1100, name: :coupler),
  Slave.from_driver(KinoEtherCAT.Driver.EL1809, name: :inputs),
  Slave.from_driver(KinoEtherCAT.Driver.EL2809, name: :outputs)
]

{:ok, _supervisor} = Simulator.start(devices: devices, udp: [ip: simulator_ip, port: 34980])

:ok = Slave.connect({:outputs, :ch1}, {:inputs, :ch1})

Kino.Layout.tabs(
  Introduction: KinoEtherCAT.introduction(),
  Simulator: KinoEtherCAT.simulator(),
  Faults: KinoEtherCAT.simulator_faults()
)
```

```mermaid
flowchart LR
  O[outputs.ch1] --> I[inputs.ch1]
```

From here on, let the setup flow create the master session and let the Master render own state and outputs.

## Keep This Picture

* EtherCAT is a coordinated cycle, not isolated device calls.
* The master owns the session.
* One tiny signal path is enough to make the process image feel real.

## Next

Add the `EtherCAT Setup` smart cell, evaluate its generated code, and continue with the `Master` render.

<!-- livebook:{"attrs":"","chunks":null,"kind":"Elixir.KinoEtherCAT.SmartCells.Setup","livebook_object":"smart_cell"} -->

```elixir
alias EtherCAT.Slave.Config, as: SlaveConfig
alias EtherCAT.Domain.Config, as: DomainConfig
udp_host = {127, 0, 0, 2}
udp_bind_ip = {127, 0, 0, 1}
# Persisted from live bus discovery.
# The notebook now boots the master from a single static EtherCAT.start/1 call.
_ = EtherCAT.stop()

setup_result =
  with :ok <-
         EtherCAT.start(
           transport: :udp,
           host: udp_host,
           port: 34980,
           bind_ip: udp_bind_ip,
           domains: [%DomainConfig{id: :main, cycle_time_us: 10000, miss_threshold: 1000}],
           dc: nil,
           slaves: [
             %SlaveConfig{name: :coupler, target_state: :op},
             %SlaveConfig{
               name: :inputs,
               driver: KinoEtherCAT.Driver.EL1809,
               process_data: {:all, :main},
               target_state: :op
             },
             %SlaveConfig{
               name: :outputs,
               driver: KinoEtherCAT.Driver.EL2809,
               process_data: {:all, :main},
               target_state: :op
             }
           ]
         ),
       :ok <- EtherCAT.await_running(),
       :ok <- EtherCAT.await_operational() do
    :ok
  end

case setup_result do
  :ok ->
    Kino.Layout.tabs(
      Master: KinoEtherCAT.master(),
      "Task Manager": KinoEtherCAT.diagnostics()
    )

  {:error, reason} ->
    _ = EtherCAT.stop()

    Kino.Markdown.new("""
    ## EtherCAT setup failed

    `#{inspect(reason)}`

    The generated setup cell kept the notebook running instead of crashing.
    Re-run the cell once the bus is stable. Configuration timeouts usually mean one or more slaves did not reach the requested state in time.
    """)
end
```
